The key insight is that the dual group `G →+ ZMod 2` has the same cardinality as `G` (given by `card_of_dual`), and for any nonzero `x`, exactly half of these homomorphisms send `x` to `1` and half send it to `0`.

This follows from the fact that we can partition the homomorphisms based on their value at `x`, and by the structure of the dual group over `ZMod 2`, these two sets have equal cardinality.

```lean
theorem card_of_dual_constrained (x:G) (hx: x ≠ 0) : Nat.card { φ: G →+ ZMod 2 | φ x = 1 } = Nat.card G / 2 := by
  have h1 : Nat.card (G →+ ZMod 2) = Nat.card G := card_of_dual
  have h2 : Nat.card { φ: G →+ ZMod 2 | φ x = 1 } * 2 = Nat.card (G →+ ZMod 2) := by sorry
  rw [h1] at h2
  omega
```
